 name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Caudry","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Arabic/Muslim Mohammad, Javaid, Kassim, Khalid, Abdul, Irshad, Muhammad, Rafiq, Shaheen, Tariq, Abdul Hamid, Adil, Alam.  Indian Anil, Asim, Ramesh, Shanti.","Indian (Bengal) and Bangladeshi: variant of   Chowdhury  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Chowdhury","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Arabic/Muslim Mohammed, Mohammad, Abdul, Abu, Iqbal, Shabbir, Abul, Ahmed, Akbar, Ali, Asif, Kamrul, Alam.  Indian Dipak, Shyamal, Deepak, Manik, Partha, Seema, Abhijeet, Ajit, Amit, Amitabha, Arun.","Indian (West Bengal) and Bangladeshi: status name for the head of a community or caste, based on Sanskrit <i>čatus-</i> ‘four-way, all-round’ + <i>dhurīya</i> (from Sanskrit <i>dhura</i> ‘burden’), i.e. ‘undertaking a burden of all-round responsibility’. The title was originally awarded by the Mughal emperors to persons of eminence, regardless of their religious affiliation. There is a Khatri clan called Chowdhury. In some traditions the term is believed to derive from a title for a military commander controlling four different fighting forces, namely navy, cavalry, infantry, and elephant corps, but this is probably no more than folk etymology."]}]},{"name":"François","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval name meaning ‘French’.  See  <b>Francis</b>   . Its popularity in France has been greatly influenced by Italian <i>Francesco</i> and the fame of St Francis of Assisi."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When François de Caudry was born in 1077, in Caudry, Nord, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France, his father, Wallérand Ier de Caudry, was 27 and his mother, Herlève de Waller